  serving size: 503
---

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200°C. Put the @bamboo skewers{4} in a #bowl{} of water to soak (this stops them burning). Chop the @potatoes{450}(chopped into 2cm wide wedges, no need to peel!). Pop the wedges on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with @oil{}, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer. Halve and peel the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and chopped into 4 - 6 wedges, layers separated). Chop the @chorizo style pork sausage{6} into bite-sized chunks, about 2cm.

Thread the onion pieces and chorizo sausage chunks onto the skewers in the following order: sausage - a couple of onion pieces - sausage pieces and so on. Tip: You are aiming for two skewers per person. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat. Pop the sausage skewers on a lightly oiled large baking tray. Roast the wedges on the top shelf of your #oven{} until golden and the skewers on the middle shelf until cooked through, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn both halfway through cooking. IMPORTANT: The sausages are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, halve the @yellow pepper{2}(halved and sliced into thin strips) and discard the core and seeds. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated, or use a garlic press). Trim the @green beans{150}(trimmed). Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the garlic and @smoked paprika{1} and cook, stirring for ~{1%minute}, then carefully pour in the @tomato passata{1}.

Pour the @water for the sauce{50} into the pan and stir in the @chicken stock paste{10}. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{} and a pinch of @sugar{pinch}, stir together then simmer the sauce until reduced, ~{3-4%minutes}. Once cooked, taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it, then remove the sauce to a bowl and cover with #foil{}. Wash your pan and pop back on medium high heat, (no oil) and add the @flaked almonds{25}.

Toast the almonds until golden, ~{2-3%minutes} - keep an eye on them! Remove to a bowl and pop your pan back on medium high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. When hot, add the green beans and stir fry until charred and soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove to a bowl and add the yellow pepper to the pan. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and fry until coloured and soft, ~{6-8%minutes}. Only stir every 2 mins.

TIP: Only stirring occasionally will help to give your peppers a lovely charred flavour!

Add the @cider vinegar{15}, @sugar{2} and @water for the beans{50} to the pan with the peppers, stir together and cook until the liquid has evaporated off, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the green beans back into the pan, stir together and cook for ~{1%minute}. Remove from the heat. Pop the beans and pepper in a bowl and top with the toasted almonds. Drizzle some of the bravas sauce over the wedges and spoon over the @mayonnaise{2}. Pop the sausage skewers on a #plate{}. Serve everything at the table 'tapas style' and enjoy!

> If there's one thing that makes us happy, it's seeing families cooking together in the kitchen! This is a great one to get kids involved in … especially threading the chorizo and veggie chunks onto the skewers, which is pretty fun (but pretty messy!).